# PRACTICE: A blog post markup

Think about how would you create an HTML markup for a page you commonly find online, like a blog post.

You start with the basic skeleton:

```html
<html>
  <body></body>
</html>

```

You add the title and subtitle:

```html
<html>
  <body>
    <h1>My nice blog post</h1>
    <h2>A subtitle</h2>
  </body>
</html>

```

and the contents of the blog post:

```html
<html>
  <body>
    <h1>My nice blog post</h1>
    <h2>A subtitle</h2>
    <p>
      Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Vivamus vulputate
      sollicitudin congue. Nunc malesuada fringilla sem eu efficitur.
      Suspendisse potenti. Suspendisse mauris dolor, aliquam ut volutpat sed,
      ultrices sit amet mauris. Donec rutrum ligula at nibh interdum, vel
      hendrerit nisi dignissim.
    </p>
  </body>
</html>

```

If you are wondering, the text is a random text from an old book, which is commonly referred to as "lorem ipsum". You can generate a few paragraphs of random text to fill your projects on [https://loremipsum.io/](https://loremipsum.io/).

Let's also wrap the page content we have now in a `main` tag.

![Screenshot 2020-04-14 at 14.33.42.png](PRACTICE%20A%20blog%20post%20markup%201902767ad7e381b48544f222cd6205c0/Screenshot_2020-04-14_at_14.33.42.png)

Next we add a navigation bar at the top, and a footer:

```html
<html>
  <body>
    <nav>
      <ol>
        <li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
        <li><a href="/blog">Blog</a></li>
      </ol>
    </nav>
    <main>
      <h1>My nice blog post</h1>
      <h2>A subtitle</h2>
      <div>
        <p>
          Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Vivamus
          vulputate sollicitudin congue. Nunc malesuada fringilla sem eu
          efficitur. Suspendisse potenti. Suspendisse mauris dolor, aliquam ut
          volutpat sed, ultrices sit amet mauris. Donec rutrum ligula at nibh
          interdum, vel hendrerit nisi dignissim.
        </p>
      </div>
    </main>
    <footer>
      <p>&copy; 2020 Flavio</p>
    </footer>
  </body>
</html>

```

Now our page is composed by

- `nav`
- `main`
- `footer`

and we can immediately infer the meaning of what's inside each tag:

![Screenshot 2020-04-14 at 14.33.06.png](PRACTICE%20A%20blog%20post%20markup%201902767ad7e381b48544f222cd6205c0/Screenshot_2020-04-14_at_14.33.06.png)

In many projects you will use `div` tags much more often.

We could also write our page using `div` elements instead of `nav/main/footer`, and the appearance (by default) would be the same. It's just less meaningful.

```html
<html>
  <body>
    <div>
      <ol>
        <li><a href="/">Home</a></li>
        <li><a href="/blog">Blog</a></li>
      </ol>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h1>My nice blog post</h1>
      <h2>A subtitle</h2>
      <div>
        <p>
          Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Vivamus
          vulputate sollicitudin congue. Nunc malesuada fringilla sem eu
          efficitur. Suspendisse potenti. Suspendisse mauris dolor, aliquam ut
          volutpat sed, ultrices sit amet mauris. Donec rutrum ligula at nibh
          interdum, vel hendrerit nisi dignissim.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p>&copy; 2020 Flavio</p>
    </div>
  </body>
</html>

```

![Screenshot 2020-04-14 at 14.29.41.png](PRACTICE%20A%20blog%20post%20markup%201902767ad7e381b48544f222cd6205c0/Screenshot_2020-04-14_at_14.29.41.png)

